{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=I-15.jpg |Ship caption=''I-15'' during her initial [[sea trial]]s }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=Japan |Ship flag= {{Shipboxflag|Empire of Japan|naval}} |Ship name=''I-15'' |Ship namesake= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder= |Ship laid down=January 1938 |Ship launched=7 March 1939 |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned=30 September 1940 |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship struck=24 December 1942 |Ship reinstated= |Ship fate=Sunk 10 November 1942 |Ship status= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class=[[Type B1 submarine]] |Ship displacement=*2,584&nbsp;tons surfaced *3,654&nbsp;tons submerged |Ship length={{convert|108.7|m|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|9.3|m|abbr=on}} |Ship draft={{convert|5.14|m|abbr=on}} |Ship propulsion=*2 diesels: {{convert|12400|hp|abbr=on}} *Electric motors: {{convert|2000|hp|abbr=on}} |Ship speed=*{{convert|23.5|kn|km/h}} surfaced *{{convert|8|kn|km/h|0}} submerged |Ship range={{convert|14000|nmi|km|-3}} at {{convert|16|kn|km/h|0}} |Ship endurance= |Ship test depth={{convert|100|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship complement=94 |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament=*6 × {{convert|533|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} forward [[torpedo tube]]s *17 [[torpedo]]es *1 × [[14 cm/40 11th Year Type naval gun]]<ref name="campbell">Campbell, John ''Naval Weapons of World War Two'' {{ISBN|0-87021-459-4}} p.191</ref> |Ship aircraft=1 [[Yokosuka E14Y]] seaplane |Ship notes= }} |} '''''I-15''''' was a Japanese [[B1 type submarine]]. She was completed at [[Kure, Hiroshima|Kure Navy Yard]] on September 30, 1940, whereupon she entered into service with the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]]. Her first and only commanding officer was Commander Nobuo Ishikawa. ''I-15'' operated off the north coast of [[Oahu]] during the [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|raid on Pearl Harbor]]. Her second wartime patrol, in May and June 1942, took her to the [[Aleutian Islands|Aleutians]], where she conducted reconnaissance of several islands. ''I-15''{{'}}s third and final patrol took place from August to November 1942, when she operated in the [[Solomon Islands]] in the South Pacific, supporting the Japanese efforts to hold [[Guadalcanal]]. One source (Morison) suggests that ''I-15'' hit the battleship {{USS|North Carolina|BB-55|6}} with a torpedo on September 15, 1942. More recent authorities (Hackett & Kingsepp) maintain that the torpedo came from another submarine operating in the area, {{Ship|Japanese submarine|I-19||2}}, which was also responsible for the sinking of {{USS|Wasp|CV-7|6}}, which ''I-15'' duly observed and reported. On November 10, 1942, a U.S. ex-destroyer (modified to a fast minesweeper), {{USS|Southard|DMS-10|6}}, sank ''I-15'' at Cape Recherche, [[Makira|San Cristóbal]], with all hands lost.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/I-15.htm | title=Imperial submarines I-15 | publisher=Combinedfleet.com | accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> Commander Ishikawa was promoted to the rank of Captain posthumously. On December 14, 1942, more than one month after ''I-15'' was sunk, {{USS|Wahoo|SS-238|6}} sank an unknown submarine which it misidentified as the ''I-15''.{{sfn|O'Kane|1987|pp=96–98}}
