{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Myron Brinig | image= | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1896|12|22|mf=yes}} | birth_place = [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], United States |death_date = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1991|05|13|1896|12|22}} | nationality = American | occupation = Novelist }}
'''Myron Brinig''' (December 22, 1896 – May 13, 1991) was a [[Ashkenazi Jews|Jewish]]-American author who wrote twenty-one novels from 1929 to 1958.<ref name="Ganz"/>
==Biography==
===Early life and education=== Brinig was born in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]] to [[Romania]]n parents, but grew up in [[Butte, Montana]].<ref name="American">{{cite book|last=Harry Redcay Warfel|title=American novelists of today|publisher=American Book Co.|year=1951|page=51|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZgoGAQAAIAAJ&dq=American+novelists+of+today&q=rumanian+parents}}</ref> Brinig began studying at [[New York University]] in 1914, where poet [[Joyce Kilmer]] gave him lectures on writing.<ref name="Ganz"/> He then studied at [[Columbia University]] and started his career by writing short stories for magazines.<ref name="Flint"/> Brinig's first novel, ''Madonna Without Child'', was released in 1929.<ref name="Ganz">{{cite web|url=http://www.glbtq.com/literature/brinig_m,2.html |title=Brinig, Myron (1896-1991) |last=Ganz |first=Earl |date=February 5, 2008 |publisher=glbtq |accessdate=2009-10-14 |location=Chicago |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705132629/http://www.glbtq.com/literature/brinig_m%2C2.html |archivedate=July 5, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Published by [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], the novel tells the story of a woman who is obsessed with another woman's baby.<ref name="Ganz"/>
===Career=== Many of Brinig's early novels depicted the settlement and development of Montana, the state he grew up in. These novels include ''Singermann'' (1929), ''Wide Open Town'' (1931), ''This Man Is My Brother'' (1932), and ''The Sun Sets in the West'' (1935).<ref name="Flint"/> Brinig based the main character of these novels, Singermann, on his father, Maurice Brinig, who was a Romanian immigrant and [[shopkeeper]].<ref name="Flint"/> Brinig's novels often depicted miners, labor organizers, farmers, and businessmen living in Montana.<ref name="Mabel">{{cite book|last=Palken Rudnick|first=Lois|title=Mabel Dodge Luhan: New Woman, New Worlds|publisher=UNM Press|year=1987|page=302|isbn=978-0-8263-0995-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8LXrhbNxlL4C&pg=PA302&dq=%22Myron+Brinig%22#v=onepage&q=%22Myron%20Brinig%22&f=false}}</ref> These usually became bestsellers in the United States and were praised by critics of ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name="Stone"/> One of the best-selling novels, ''The Sisters'', was adapted to [[The Sisters (1938 film)|a feature-length film]] in 1938, starring [[Bette Davis]] and [[Errol Flynn]].<ref name="Flint"/>
Brinig's novels often dealt with homosexuality.<ref name="Ganz"/><ref name="Taos">{{cite book|last=Ganz|first=Earl|title=The Taos Truth Game|publisher=University of New Mexico Press|year= 2007|isbn=978-0-8263-3772-6}}</ref><ref name="Slide">{{cite book|last=Slide|first=Anthony|title=Lost Gay Novels|publisher=Routledge|year=2003|isbn=978-1-56023-414-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6Dj1cA_vkV4C&pg=PA34&dq=%22Myron+Brinig%22#v=onepage&q=%22Myron%20Brinig%22&f=false}}</ref> It was a common theme for Brinig because he was a homosexual himself (although he was publicly [[closeted]] all his life).<ref name="Ganz"/> According to the [[Gay & Lesbian Literary Heritage]], Brinig was the "first American Jewish novelist to write in any significant way about the gay experience."<ref name="Stone">{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb3491/is_4_13/ai_n29323372/|title=Desert salon|last=E. Stone|first=Martha|date=July–August 2006 |work=The Gay & Lesbian Review Worldwide|accessdate=2009-10-14}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>
In 1951, ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' said Brinig's "sentimental streak and his sympathetic touch with characters usually lend his books a warm glow of humanity, if not of art."<ref name="Flint"/> At the beginning of his career, Brinig was praised by critics for his "artistry and inventivenss in narrative, character and incident."<ref name="Flint"/> In the early 1930s, he was described as one of the leading young writers in America.<ref name="Mabel"/> Brinig's last novels, however, were met with mixed reviews from critics, who criticized them for their "verbosity and banality."<ref name="Flint"/> Brinig died on May 13, 1991. The cause of his death was [[gastrointestinal hemorrhage]].<ref name="Flint">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/05/15/obituaries/myron-brinig-94-novelist-noted-for-works-on-montana-s-infancy.html|title=Myron Brinig, 94, Novelist Noted For Works on Montana's Infancy|last=Flint|first=Peter|date=May 15, 1991|work=[[The New York Times]]|page=D25|accessdate=2009-10-14|location=New York}}</ref>
